APPENDIX A — METHODS AND COLAB TESTS
------------------------------------------------------------

Numerical tests were performed using SPARC galaxy data within Google
Colab.

A.1 Baseline cumulative-stiffness profile tests

The early cumulative-stiffness tests used the unweighted map

    S(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds

and recovered corrected master-curve exponents

    power-law stiffness         ν = 0.940
    density-coupled stiffness   ν = 0.947
    exponential-core stiffness  ν = 0.950.


A.2 Local baryonic loading field

The later SPARC tests found an empirical baryonic loading law

    m_b(r) = ( g_b(r) / g_* )^γ

with

    γ ≈ 0.34.


A.3 Effective weighted cumulative operator

An effective weighted operator of the form

    S(r) = ∫_0^r s^κ m_b(s) ds

with

    κ ≈ −0.2

was found to reproduce the pooled master curve and weighted horizon
relations. Subsequent analysis showed that this operator is best
interpreted as an effective Euclidean-radius representation rather
than the fundamental law.


A.4 Kernel reconstruction tests

Both parametric and nonparametric kernel reconstructions were carried
out directly from the working sample.

These tests did not support a universal interior kernel of the form

    Φ(x) ∝ x^(−0.2).

Galaxy-by-galaxy reconstructions instead showed substantial scatter and
a trimmed median kernel shape closer to weakly positive slope, with no
evidence for a universal negative exponent. This ruled out the
weighted-kernel interpretation as fundamental.


A.5 Source-coordinate reduction

The decisive later tests introduced the cumulative baryonic stiffness
coordinate

    u(r) = ∫_0^r ( g_b(s) / g_* )^γ ds

and examined the response field as a function of u.

The principal results were:

    median linear R^2(S vs u)      ≈ 0.9993
    mean linear R^2(S vs u)        ≈ 0.9957
    trimmed median CV(dS/du)       ≈ 0.053

showing that the response is nearly linear in u.


A.6 Zero-free-parameter response law

Using the normalized law

    S(r) = u(r) / u(R_s)

the parameter-free prediction

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−u(r)/u(R_s)]

was tested directly against the validated pooled master-curve target.

The results were

    median RMSE                    ≈ 0.044
    mean RMSE                      ≈ 0.053
    pooled ν_pred                  ≈ 0.961
    pooled x_0_pred                ≈ 0.979.

This is the strongest direct empirical support for the source-
coordinate formulation.


A.7 Interpretation of earlier metric and weighted formulations

Several effective-theory and metric-closure constructions were also
explored during the Colab sequence, including weighted operators,
effective kernels, and self-consistent metric-response closures.

These constructions were useful intermediate descriptions, but the
later source-coordinate reduction showed that they are not required as
fundamental laws once the natural cumulative baryonic stiffness
coordinate u is used.



